Penetration testing is incomplete without network analysis. These commands are used to check connections.

9. ip a (IP Address Check)
In simple terms: Viewing your machine's IP address (whether via WiFi or Ethernet).
Practical Example: Determining your subnet so you can scan other computers.

Bash
ip a
10. ss -tulpn (Socket Statistics)
In simple terms: "Who is my computer secretly communicating with, and which path (port) is open?"

Practical Example: Checking if any backdoor or unauthorized service is running on your Kali Linux system:
Bash
sudo ss -tulpn
